1
00:00:04,280 --> 00:00:05,918
- Are we done?
- Listen, I -

2
00:00:06,120 --> 00:00:10,033
This attack on my brother-in-law, I don't know what it means.

3
00:00:10,240 --> 00:00:11,912
Please.

4
00:00:12,840 --> 00:00:15,195
I fear for my family.

5
00:00:15,520 --> 00:00:17,795
I'm sure they'll be fine.

6
00:00:18,280 --> 00:00:21,636
I'm told the assassin that survived is gravely injured.

7
00:00:21,840 --> 00:00:23,751
It's doubtful he'll live.

8
00:00:24,520 --> 00:00:27,478
Now, thank me and shake my hand.

9
00:00:29,560 --> 00:00:33,712
- Thank you. Thank you again.
- You're quite welcome, Mr. White.

10
00:00:34,600 --> 00:00:36,636
Guys, guys, hurry up.

11
00:00:36,840 --> 00:00:39,673
- Can we go now?
- Upstairs, come on.

12
00:00:40,600 --> 00:00:42,272
What's happening?

13
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:44,194
Eight forty-three.

14
00:00:44,400 --> 00:00:47,437
Time of death, 20:43.

15
00:00:48,440 --> 00:00:50,635
Burn in hell, you piece of shit.

16
00:00:56,960 --> 00:00:59,076
One of the gunmen died at the scene.

17
00:00:59,280 --> 00:01:02,352
The second succumbed to his wounds earlier this evening.

18
00:01:02,560 --> 00:01:04,118
Agents with the DEA and FBI...

19
00:01:04,320 --> 00:01:08,074
...in conjunction with APD are working
with Mexican law enforcement...

20
00:01:08,280 --> 00:01:11,989
...in an attempt to identify the deceased suspects. Both -

21
00:01:29,040 --> 00:01:31,235
I can give you the highlights.

22
00:01:32,120 --> 00:01:33,997
Your nephews grew impatient.

23
00:01:34,200 --> 00:01:37,636
They continued to press me for my permission to kill Walter White.

24
00:01:37,840 --> 00:01:42,277
When I wouldn't give it, they settled
instead for DEA Agent Schrader.

25
00:01:43,320 --> 00:01:45,231
But a phone call was placed...

26
00:01:45,440 --> 00:01:48,000
...to Agent Schrader moments before the attack.

27
00:01:48,200 --> 00:01:50,634
Thus giving him the upper hand.

28
00:01:50,840 --> 00:01:53,673
Marco was shot in the face and died instantly.

29
00:01:53,880 --> 00:01:56,792
Leonel lingered for several hours.

30
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:00,673
The warning call to the DEA agent...

31
00:02:01,560 --> 00:02:04,393
...Juan Bolsa may have some insight...

32
00:02:04,600 --> 00:02:06,591
...into who placed it.

33
00:02:06,800 --> 00:02:08,916
Yesterday, federales raided his hacienda.

34
00:02:09,120 --> 00:02:12,032
And in the confusion, Juan was shot dead.

35
00:02:12,560 --> 00:02:14,755
An accident, perhaps.

36
00:02:15,280 --> 00:02:18,352
A mistake made by his own men.

37
00:02:18,960 --> 00:02:20,916
Though we may never know.

38
00:02:21,640 --> 00:02:24,632
At any rate, I thought you should hear it from me.

39
00:02:33,880 --> 00:02:37,919
This is what comes of blood for blood, Hector.

40
00:03:28,760 --> 00:03:30,796
So is this the loud one?

41
00:03:33,160 --> 00:03:34,309
What?

42
00:03:34,520 --> 00:03:36,511
I can never remember.

43
00:03:36,720 --> 00:03:40,349
Is this the loud machine with the magnets?

44
00:03:40,560 --> 00:03:43,074
No. This is the PET/CT scan.

45
00:03:43,280 --> 00:03:46,477
Positron emission tomography.

46
00:03:48,200 --> 00:03:54,878
They've paired that with computed x-ray tomography.

47
00:03:56,560 --> 00:03:59,028
Quiet. No magnets.

48
00:03:59,280 --> 00:04:00,952
Right, okay.

49
00:04:01,160 --> 00:04:02,354
Yeah, thanks.

50
00:04:04,240 --> 00:04:06,071
I'm still pretty new at this.

51
00:04:06,520 --> 00:04:08,636
One minute, I'm starting a new business...

52
00:04:08,840 --> 00:04:10,910
...my wife and I are thinking about kids.

53
00:04:11,120 --> 00:04:13,588
Walk into a doctor's office and suddenly...

54
00:04:13,800 --> 00:04:16,951
- I mean, life as I know it -
- Excuse me.

55
00:04:17,600 --> 00:04:20,433
Yes. I'm waiting to hear a progress report...

56
00:04:20,640 --> 00:04:24,155
...on the thing we discussed, so call me.

57
00:04:27,760 --> 00:04:30,911
Anyway, so for me, that's been the biggest wake-up call.

58
00:04:31,120 --> 00:04:33,918
Letting go, giving up control.

59
00:04:34,120 --> 00:04:37,954
You know, it's like they say, "Man plans and God laughs."

60
00:04:38,640 --> 00:04:42,713
That is such bullshit.

61
00:04:43,200 --> 00:04:44,394
Excuse me?

62
00:04:44,600 --> 00:04:46,989
Never give up control.

63
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:50,798
Live life on your own terms.

64
00:04:51,560 --> 00:04:53,915
Yeah, no, I get what you're saying...

65
00:04:54,120 --> 00:04:56,156
...but cancer is cancer, so...

66
00:04:56,360 --> 00:04:58,271
To hell with your cancer.

67
00:04:58,720 --> 00:05:01,393
I've been living with cancer for the better part of a year.

68
00:05:01,600 --> 00:05:05,309
From the start, it's a death sentence.
That's what they keep telling me.

69
00:05:05,520 --> 00:05:07,112
Well, guess what?

70
00:05:07,320 --> 00:05:10,471
Every life comes with a death sentence.

71
00:05:10,680 --> 00:05:14,832
So every few months, I come in here for my regular scan...

72
00:05:15,040 --> 00:05:18,715
...knowing full well that one of these times -

73
00:05:18,920 --> 00:05:21,195
Hell, maybe even today.

74
00:05:22,400 --> 00:05:24,914
I'm gonna hear some bad news.

75
00:05:25,160 --> 00:05:26,991
But until then...

76
00:05:27,560 --> 00:05:29,198
...who's in charge?

77
00:05:29,600 --> 00:05:30,999
Me.

78
00:05:33,680 --> 00:05:35,910
That's how I live my life.

79
00:05:52,880 --> 00:05:55,678
This residue here is why we descale with cool water...

80
00:05:55,880 --> 00:05:58,269
...from the walk-in and not water from the tap.

81
00:05:58,480 --> 00:06:00,232
Do it again, please.

82
00:06:03,040 --> 00:06:06,237
Pollos Hermanos, where something delicious is always cooking.

83
00:06:07,680 --> 00:06:09,477
Yes, detective.

84
00:06:32,920 --> 00:06:34,069
Yeah.

85
00:06:35,840 --> 00:06:37,796
- Gustavo, thanks for coming.
- Pleasure.

86
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:40,389
- How's Kathi?
- Much better, thank you.

87
00:06:40,600 --> 00:06:43,160
- And you know Hank Schrader?
- Yes, indeed.

88
00:06:43,360 --> 00:06:45,669
- And Steve Gomez?
- How was your meal?

89
00:06:45,880 --> 00:06:48,952
Agent Schrader and I had a chance to
catch up at one of my restaurants.

90
00:06:49,160 --> 00:06:52,357
I'd eat there every day but I wouldn't fit through the door.

91
00:06:52,600 --> 00:06:54,477
- Well, should we get started?
- Yeah.

92
00:06:56,120 --> 00:06:59,351
- I'd like to record this conversation.
- Of course.

93
00:07:03,360 --> 00:07:08,514
The DEA is working on an investigation
which may overlap with my own...

94
00:07:08,720 --> 00:07:10,358
...so I've asked them to sit in.

95
00:07:10,560 --> 00:07:14,030
Gus, we all appreciate your coming in here to talk to us...

96
00:07:14,240 --> 00:07:16,993
...but you have the right to have an attorney present.

97
00:07:17,200 --> 00:07:20,272
Oh, well, I can't see how that would be necessary.

98
00:07:20,480 --> 00:07:22,391
But then, I have no idea why I'm here.

99
00:07:22,600 --> 00:07:24,113
So you wish to continue?

100
00:07:24,320 --> 00:07:28,836
Please. I'm very anxious to find out what this is all about.

101
00:07:29,080 --> 00:07:32,516
Sir, your fingerprints were found at a crime scene.

102
00:07:32,960 --> 00:07:35,838
Really? That's surprising.

103
00:07:36,040 --> 00:07:38,554
A drug-related homicide.

104
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:46,560
Gale Boetticher's apartment.

105
00:07:50,560 --> 00:07:52,152
So you knew the victim?

106
00:07:56,760 --> 00:08:01,117
Fifteen years ago, I established a chemistry scholarship at UNM.

107
00:08:01,320 --> 00:08:03,880
I named it after Maximino Arciniega...

108
00:08:04,080 --> 00:08:06,116
...a dear friend of mine who died young.

109
00:08:06,440 --> 00:08:08,749
Gale was a recipient of this scholarship.

110
00:08:08,960 --> 00:08:12,919
He was perhaps one of three dozen.

111
00:08:13,120 --> 00:08:14,758
I see.

112
00:08:15,400 --> 00:08:19,279
And Mr. Boetticher graduated in...

113
00:08:19,480 --> 00:08:22,153
- 1999.
- That sounds right.

114
00:08:22,360 --> 00:08:25,158
And you kept in contact with him over all this time?

115
00:08:25,360 --> 00:08:29,717
Oh, no. I hadn't seen Gale for years
until I ran into him a few weeks ago.

116
00:08:29,920 --> 00:08:32,798
- Ran into him where?
- At the restaurant.

117
00:08:33,680 --> 00:08:36,592
Well, "ran into" isn't quite accurate, as I assumed...

118
00:08:36,800 --> 00:08:40,588
...he came by to re-establish contact
with me. We caught up briefly.

119
00:08:40,800 --> 00:08:44,349
He invited me to dinner the following night and I accepted.

120
00:08:45,800 --> 00:08:49,679
It was perhaps a week later when I read about him in the paper.

121
00:08:49,880 --> 00:08:52,553
- Drug related, you said?
- It's a good possibility.

122
00:08:52,760 --> 00:08:54,910
The paper made no mention of that.

123
00:08:55,120 --> 00:08:57,680
I assumed that it was a random crime.

124
00:08:57,880 --> 00:09:01,873
So after years with no contact, he shows up in your restaurant...

125
00:09:02,080 --> 00:09:05,277
- ...and invites you to dinner?
- He wanted money.

126
00:09:05,480 --> 00:09:08,278
- Gale Boetticher asked for money?
- He didn't say that.

127
00:09:08,640 --> 00:09:13,191
He spoke in terms of a vague investment opportunity.

128
00:09:13,400 --> 00:09:17,234
But it was my suspicion, yes,
as to why he invited me into his home.

129
00:09:17,440 --> 00:09:22,514
He was a very, very talented chemist,
but for reasons I never understood...

130
00:09:22,720 --> 00:09:25,632
...he was more interested in taking shortcuts...

131
00:09:25,840 --> 00:09:29,389
...than what would or could have been a very promising career.

132
00:09:29,600 --> 00:09:31,636
Personal shortcomings notwithstanding...

133
00:09:31,840 --> 00:09:33,910
...he was a warm, gentle person...

134
00:09:34,120 --> 00:09:36,395
...and I thought a lot of him.

135
00:09:38,360 --> 00:09:42,319
At any rate, I declined his business offer...

136
00:09:42,520 --> 00:09:45,717
...and after what was a very pleasant meal, left.

137
00:09:46,280 --> 00:09:47,998
Can you tell us where you were...

138
00:09:48,200 --> 00:09:51,636
...on the night of Wednesday the 23rd at around 8 p.m.?

139
00:09:51,840 --> 00:09:56,311
- Not an accusation, just a question.
- No, I understand. Let's see.

140
00:09:58,400 --> 00:09:59,958
Twenty-third.

141
00:10:01,240 --> 00:10:03,834
I was at a fundraiser at Presbyterian Hospital.

142
00:10:04,040 --> 00:10:06,600
I was there from 7 to about 10.

143
00:10:10,800 --> 00:10:12,631
Anyone else?

144
00:10:15,560 --> 00:10:18,199
Sorry, yeah. Just one other thing.

145
00:10:18,680 --> 00:10:21,148
Is Gustavo Fring your real name?

146
00:10:23,320 --> 00:10:24,992
Is it my real name?

147
00:10:25,200 --> 00:10:28,715
I know you're a Chilean national...

148
00:10:28,920 --> 00:10:31,957
...but there are no records of you ever living there.

149
00:10:32,640 --> 00:10:34,073
Really?

150
00:10:34,400 --> 00:10:38,871
I mean, records show that you immigrated to Mexico in 1986...

151
00:10:39,080 --> 00:10:43,278
...and years later, you were granted
an entry visa to the United States.

152
00:10:43,480 --> 00:10:49,271
But there's no record of Gustavo
Fring ever having existed in Chile...

153
00:10:49,480 --> 00:10:52,358
...which I find, I don't know, strange.

154
00:10:52,840 --> 00:10:54,831
Well, no, really, it isn't.

155
00:10:55,360 --> 00:10:57,954
Pinochet's government was guilty of many sins.

156
00:10:58,160 --> 00:11:00,390
First and foremost were human rights abuses.

157
00:11:00,920 --> 00:11:04,310
But it was also notoriously unreliable at keeping records.

158
00:11:05,560 --> 00:11:08,358
I'm sure if you keep digging, you'll find me.

159
00:11:11,160 --> 00:11:13,594
Okay, I think that's it, Gus. Thank you.

160
00:11:13,800 --> 00:11:16,234
I hope that I was of some small help.

161
00:11:16,440 --> 00:11:19,830
- You were, absolutely. Thank you.
- You're very welcome.

162
00:11:20,040 --> 00:11:21,598
Good to see you again. Oh, no.

163
00:11:21,800 --> 00:11:24,155
- No, please, please. Don't get up.
- Thanks.

164
00:11:29,240 --> 00:11:30,753
Gentlemen.

165
00:11:52,280 --> 00:11:54,396
So are we buying?

166
00:11:54,600 --> 00:11:56,795
This thing with his name? What are you thinking?

167
00:11:57,000 --> 00:11:59,958
Sure, the record-keeping in South America's hit or miss.

168
00:12:00,160 --> 00:12:02,515
I mean, we run into that all the time, right?

169
00:12:02,720 --> 00:12:06,269
But we usually find something. Before '86 this guy's a ghost.

170
00:12:06,480 --> 00:12:10,314
If State Department wasn't satisfied,
they wouldn't have naturalised him.

171
00:12:10,520 --> 00:12:13,830
Well, maybe, but he emigrated from Mexico in '89.

172
00:12:14,040 --> 00:12:17,191
State just wasn't as tough on background checks pre-9/11.

173
00:12:17,400 --> 00:12:20,472
I don't know what this has to do with the case at hand.

174
00:12:20,680 --> 00:12:24,275
I was curious when his print showed up at Boetticher's apartment.

175
00:12:24,480 --> 00:12:26,436
For me, the scholarship explains it.

176
00:12:26,640 --> 00:12:28,790
I'll admit to a certain degree of bias.

177
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:31,798
This man has been a longtime friend of DEA.

178
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:36,710
But that being said, I thought his story was credible.

179
00:12:37,120 --> 00:12:39,554
Well, I agree. I think it was a good story.

180
00:12:39,760 --> 00:12:41,830
Still, why are we hearing it now?

181
00:12:42,040 --> 00:12:42,995
What do you mean?

182
00:12:43,200 --> 00:12:47,637
Well, like you said, he's a-
This man is a big law enforcement booster.

183
00:12:47,840 --> 00:12:51,469
He's reading the newspaper and sees
that someone he had dinner with...

184
00:12:51,680 --> 00:12:54,148
...someone he thought a lot of was murdered.

185
00:12:54,360 --> 00:12:57,033
He reads this and he doesn't make a phone call?

186
00:12:57,480 --> 00:13:01,439
Didn't call you or one of his other cop friends...

187
00:13:01,640 --> 00:13:05,394
...to share his connection with the
case or ask about the investigation?

188
00:13:05,600 --> 00:13:08,558
We can't predicate a criminal investigation...

189
00:13:08,760 --> 00:13:10,796
...on a person not making phone calls.

190
00:13:12,560 --> 00:13:14,118
What do you think, Tim?

191
00:13:14,320 --> 00:13:17,995
Well, I wanna follow up on the scholarship, the alibi...

192
00:13:18,200 --> 00:13:20,077
...but my overall impression?

193
00:13:20,280 --> 00:13:21,395
I believed him.

194
00:13:31,240 --> 00:13:34,596
Nice touch. Birdbath.

195
00:13:35,840 --> 00:13:38,400
- Hey, tiger, how's it hanging?
- Good.

196
00:13:40,280 --> 00:13:43,192
Yeah, so very nice.

197
00:13:43,400 --> 00:13:45,436
What's the damage?

198
00:13:45,800 --> 00:13:48,519
Twelve hundred a month. I did a lot of research.

199
00:13:48,720 --> 00:13:52,190
- That's a pretty good deal.
- You kidding me? That's a great deal.

200
00:13:52,400 --> 00:13:54,197
Speaking of which...

201
00:13:54,680 --> 00:13:56,511
...that's for the week.

202
00:13:56,720 --> 00:14:00,349
Plus there's a little extra in there
for any move-related incidentals.

203
00:14:00,560 --> 00:14:01,549
Thank you.

204
00:14:02,200 --> 00:14:04,998
- Hey, champ, how's the new school?
- Good.

205
00:14:05,200 --> 00:14:07,031
I loved school when I was your age.

206
00:14:07,240 --> 00:14:10,710
Seesaws, story time, chasing girls with sticks.

207
00:14:20,160 --> 00:14:24,597
It wasn't until the fifth grade
that I found out she liked me too...

208
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:28,549
...but by then her family had moved to Scottsdale, so...

209
00:14:30,800 --> 00:14:32,995
- Carpe diem, okay?
- Okay.

210
00:14:33,200 --> 00:14:34,633
All right. Good boy.

211
00:14:35,760 --> 00:14:38,991
So you'll thank Jesse again from both of us?

212
00:14:39,200 --> 00:14:40,474
You got it.

213
00:14:41,920 --> 00:14:45,151
- So is he- How's he doing?
- Jesse?

214
00:14:50,520 --> 00:14:55,036
He's good. He's busy.

215
00:15:03,160 --> 00:15:04,434
How is it?

216
00:15:04,640 --> 00:15:09,270
Space, lots of light. It's - Little garden out back. It's nice.

217
00:15:10,320 --> 00:15:13,551
And Brock? How's he doing?

218
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:16,992
Hey, look, I don't mind dropping cheques off every week...

219
00:15:17,200 --> 00:15:18,553
...like Ed McMahon...

220
00:15:18,760 --> 00:15:21,035
...but if you wanna know how they're doing...

221
00:15:21,240 --> 00:15:23,879
...why don't you go see for yourself?

222
00:15:28,680 --> 00:15:29,999
I'll catch you later.

223
00:15:31,360 --> 00:15:33,828
- Hey, you gonna need a ride home?
- No.

224
00:16:17,360 --> 00:16:18,634
Great.

225
00:16:22,720 --> 00:16:25,314
Anyway, I'm proud for not losing my cool.

226
00:16:25,520 --> 00:16:28,239
Plus, it shows our crew that I will support them...

227
00:16:28,440 --> 00:16:30,192
...if a customer's being rude.

228
00:16:30,400 --> 00:16:33,676
You're really taking to this whole be-your-own-boss thing.

229
00:16:34,160 --> 00:16:37,197
Yeah. I guess I am.

230
00:16:37,680 --> 00:16:39,352
Actually...

231
00:16:40,040 --> 00:16:43,396
...I'm thinking about making the move up to management.

232
00:16:43,600 --> 00:16:45,397
Jesus. Corporate America, look out.

233
00:16:45,600 --> 00:16:48,160
Excuse me, I would be a vast improvement.

234
00:16:48,360 --> 00:16:52,114
No one in Kleinman's entire front
office knows about giving an x-ray...

235
00:16:52,320 --> 00:16:53,878
...which is just...

236
00:16:54,280 --> 00:16:56,874
Hey, Dad, whatever happened with your scan?

237
00:16:57,080 --> 00:16:59,071
Did you get the results back?

238
00:17:00,040 --> 00:17:03,271
Yeah, I did...

239
00:17:03,480 --> 00:17:05,550
...and I'm still in remission.

240
00:17:05,760 --> 00:17:10,072
So you're all gonna have to be stuck with me for a while longer.

241
00:17:10,280 --> 00:17:11,269
Cheers, buddy.

242
00:17:13,600 --> 00:17:16,160
What about you, Hank? How you feeling these days?

243
00:17:16,360 --> 00:17:18,271
You know, getting there.

244
00:17:18,480 --> 00:17:22,792
The other day, he had a big powwow with all the DEA muckety-mucks.

245
00:17:23,680 --> 00:17:25,352
What was that about?

246
00:17:25,800 --> 00:17:28,473
Nothing. Just a dead-end.

247
00:17:28,680 --> 00:17:30,318
He won't tell me, either.

248
00:17:30,520 --> 00:17:32,511
Apparently, it's all very hush-hush.

249
00:17:33,720 --> 00:17:36,553
Hey, Walt, do me a favour?

250
00:17:37,680 --> 00:17:40,877
Marie's working tomorrow and there's a gem and mineral show...

251
00:17:41,080 --> 00:17:45,358
...opening at the fairgrounds.
